      <div class="legal-section">
        <h2>10. Investment Risks</h2>
        <p><strong>10.1 KEY RISKS STATEMENT:</strong> The value of investments can go down as well as up, and you may receive back less than the original amount invested. Past performance is not a reliable indicator of future results.</p>
        <p><strong>10.2</strong> The monthly income you receive from the EPM is derived from investment returns and is therefore subject to market fluctuations. The income amount is not guaranteed and may vary from month to month.</p>
        <p><strong>10.3</strong> Specific risks associated with the EPM investment strategy include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>(a) <strong>Market Risk:</strong> The value of the investment portfolio may decline due to adverse market conditions;</li>
          <li>(b) <strong>Income Risk:</strong> Monthly income payments may be reduced or suspended if investment returns are insufficient;</li>
          <li>(c) <strong>Currency Risk:</strong> As the investment portfolio includes international ETFs, exchange rate fluctuations may affect returns;</li>
          <li>(d) <strong>Counterparty Risk:</strong> The risk that an investment counterparty or insurer may fail to meet its obligations;</li>
          <li>(e) <strong>Liquidity Risk:</strong> In exceptional market conditions, it may not be possible to liquidate investments at the expected price.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>10.4</strong> The hedging collar strategy mitigates but does not eliminate downside risk. The collar provides a floor on investment losses but also caps potential gains above a specified level.</p>
        <p><strong>10.5</strong> CAPITAL AT RISK: Your capital is at risk. The NNEG insurance ensures you will never owe more than the value of your property, but investment returns are not guaranteed.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="legal-section">
        <h2>11. Holiday Mechanism</h2>
        <p><strong>11.1</strong> The EPM includes a Holiday Mechanism that allows you to temporarily suspend or reduce monthly income payments under the following conditions:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>(a) You may request an income holiday for a period of up to [X] months in any [Y]-year period;</li>
          <li>(b) During an income holiday, no monthly income will be paid, but the investment portfolio will continue to be managed;</li>
          <li>(c) Unpaid income during a holiday period may be accumulated and paid at a later date, or may be retained within the investment portfolio, subject to the terms of your mortgage offer;</li>
          <li>(d) We may require that a minimum investment portfolio value is maintained before approving an income holiday request.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>11.2</strong> To request an income holiday, you must provide us with at least [X] days' written notice.</p>
        <p><strong>11.3</strong> We reserve the right to refuse a holiday request if, in our reasonable assessment, granting the request would materially prejudice your financial position.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="legal-section">
        <h2>12. Insurance and No Negative Equity Guarantee (NNEG)</h2>
        <p><strong>12.1</strong> The EPM includes a No Negative Equity Guarantee (NNEG), which ensures that you will never owe more than the market value of your property at the time of repayment.</p>
        <p><strong>12.2</strong> The NNEG is provided through a combination of:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>(a) A dedicated insurance product underwritten by [insurer details];</li>
          <li>(b) A pooled risk mechanism across the FutureProof portfolio;</li>
          <li>(c) The hedging collar on the investment portfolio.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>12.3</strong> The cost of the NNEG insurance is incorporated into the overall fee structure of the EPM and is disclosed in your mortgage offer and KFI.</p>
        <p><strong>12.4</strong> The NNEG applies at the point of mortgage repayment (whether at term end, voluntary early repayment, sale of the property, or the death of the Borrower). If the outstanding loan balance exceeds the property value at that time, the shortfall is covered by the NNEG.</p>
        <p><strong>12.5</strong> You are not required to make any additional payment beyond the value of your property to discharge the mortgage.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="legal-section">
        <h2>13. Property Obligations</h2>
        <p><strong>13.1</strong> Throughout the term of the EPM, you are required to:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>(a) <strong>Building Insurance:</strong> Maintain comprehensive buildings insurance for the full reinstatement value of the property with a reputable insurer, noting FutureProof's interest on the policy;</li>
          <li>(b) <strong>Council Tax:</strong> Pay all council tax (or rates in Northern Ireland) due on the property;</li>
          <li>(c) <strong>Ground Rent and Service Charges:</strong> If the property is leasehold, pay all ground rent, service charges, and other leasehold obligations as they fall due;</li>
          <li>(d) <strong>Property Maintenance:</strong> Maintain the property in a good state of repair and not permit waste or deterioration that would materially affect its value;</li>
          <li>(e) <strong>Land Registry:</strong> Ensure the property remains registered with HM Land Registry (or the equivalent registry in Scotland or Northern Ireland) and that the mortgage charge is properly recorded;</li>
          <li>(f) <strong>Occupancy:</strong> Maintain the property as your primary residence and notify us immediately if this changes;</li>
          <li>(g) <strong>Structural Alterations:</strong> Obtain our prior written consent before making any material structural alterations to the property;</li>
          <li>(h) <strong>Planning and Building Regulations:</strong> Comply with all applicable planning permissions, building regulations, and local authority requirements.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>13.2</strong> Failure to comply with these obligations may constitute a breach of the mortgage terms and may result in the mortgage becoming repayable.</p>
      </div>

